last edition. This book is distinguished from others in the field by its breadth of coverage, compelling institutional history, and lively prose style. It opens with a chapter on schooling as a social institution. Subsequent chapters compare schooling in industrialized and developing countries, and discuss the major purposes of schooling: transmitting culture, socializing young people, and sorting youth for class locations and occupations. The penultimate chapter looks at school reform efforts, drawing for the first time on comparative studies. A new coda ends the book by considering the educational ideals schools should strive for and how they might be attained. This third edition of Schools and Societies delivers the accessible explanations instructors rely on with updated, expanded information that's even more relevant for students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aComparative education. 0aEducational sociologyvCross-cultural studies. 0aEducational sociologyzUnited States. 0aSchoolsxSociological aspectsvCross-cultural studies. 0aSchoolszUnited StatesxSociological aspects. 4acomparative-historical analysis. 4acultural transmission. 4ainstitutional analysis. 4aschooling. 4asocial selection. 4asocialization. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360103140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601031.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles